body:
In old English law.
The act of banishing or turning out of doors;
rejection.

In criminal law. This
offense consists in the attempt to influence a
jury corruptly to one side or the other, by
promises, persuasions, entreaties, entertainments, douceurs, and the like. The person
guilty of it is called an "embraceor." Brown;
State v. Williams, 1386 Mo. 203, 38 S. W. 75;
Grannis v. Branden, 5 Day (Conn.) 274, 5 Am,
Dec. 143; State v. Brown, 95 N. C. 686;
Brown v. Beauchamp, 5 T. B. Mon. (Ky.) 415,
17 Am. Dec. 81.

In the civil law. The
person to whom an emphyteusis is granted;

the lessee or tenant under a contract of emphyteusis.

In old English law. To
outlaw; to deprive one of the benefit and
protection of the law, (exuere aliquem beneftcio legis.) Spelman.;

In the civillaw. To spoil;
to rob or plunder. Applied to inheritances.
Dig. 47, 19; Cod. 9, 32.

To lessen; to palliate;
to mitigate. Connell v. State, 46 Tex. Cr.
R. 250, 81 8S. W. 748.

Out of abundance;
abundantly; superfluously; more than sufficient. Calvin.

EX ABUNDANTI CAUTELA. Lat.
Out of abundant caution. "The practice
has arisen abundanté cauicla." 8 East, 326;
Lord Ellenborough, 4 Maule & S. 544.
